    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How do I track my protein intake for a week?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Log every protein source immediately after eating for 7 consecutive days. Note the food, the portion, and the grams of protein. A dedicated protein tracker makes this 30 seconds per meal. At the end of each day, compare your total to your target. Most men find the gap within the first 2–3 days.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What do most men over 40 discover when they track protein?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">The most consistent discovery is a 30–50g daily gap between estimated and actual intake. Most men believe they eat 100–120g per day. Tracked honestly, the number is typically 65–85g. The gap almost always appears at breakfast and lunch — not dinner.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much protein should men over 40 eat per day?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Research supports 1.2–1.6g of protein per kilogram of bodyweight for men over 40. For a 180-pound man, that's 98–131g per day. The per-meal target matters as much as the daily total — each meal should deliver 30–40g to reliably trigger muscle protein synthesis after 40.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Why do men over 40 underestimate their protein intake?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Three reasons: breakfast is consistently underdosed but feels adequate (2 eggs = 12g, not 30g); lunch typically consists of convenience foods with lower protein density than perceived; and dinner's protein is overestimated because the portion looks large. Without the actual number, the mental model of "eating well" doesn't flag the gaps.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is 7 days enough to understand your protein intake patterns?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — 7 days is enough to identify consistent patterns and gaps. Most men find their issues are structural rather than random. A week of data shows which meal is your weakest link and gives you enough information to fix it. After 7 days, many men continue because the habit becomes effortless and the daily feedback is genuinely valuable.</div>
